# Convex Organization

## File Structure

```sh
convex/
├─ categories.ts       # Category queries & mutations
├─ http.ts             # HTTP endpoints (webhooks)
├─ items.ts            # Item queries & mutations
├─ schema.ts           # Database schema
├─ users.ts            # User queries
├─ lib/
│  ├─ permissions.ts   # Authorization helpers
│  └─ validation.ts    # Server-side validation
└─ _generated/         # Auto-generated
```

## Naming Conventions

### Query Functions (reads)

Describe the data operation:

```ts
export const get = query(...)         // Get single by ID
export const getBySlug = query(...)   // Get by other field
export const list = query(...)        // Get collection
export const search = query(...)      // Filtered list
```

### Mutation Functions (writes)

Use action verbs:

```ts
export const archive = mutation(...)  // Specific action
export const create = mutation(...)   // Create new
export const publish = mutation(...)  // Specific action
export const remove = mutation(...)   // Delete (avoid "delete" keyword)
export const toggle = mutation(...)   // Toggle state
export const update = mutation(...)   // Update existing
```

### Function Naming Examples

```ts
// ✅ Clear
export const getBySlug = query(...)
export const list = query(...)

// ❌ Vague
export const data = query(...)
export const stuff = query(...)

// ✅ Concise
export const get = query(...)            // api.items.get
export const list = query(...)           // api.items.list

// ❌ Redundant (file provides context)
export const getItem = query(...)        // in items.ts
export const listItems = query(...)      // in items.ts
```

## Database Schema Conventions

### Field Naming

Name fields by what they reference:

```ts
items: defineTable({
  categoryId: v.id('categories'),
  statusId: v.id('statuses'),
  userId: v.id('user'), // or authorId, be consistent
});
```

### Index Naming

Name indexes by what you're querying:

```ts
.index('by_category', ['categoryId'])
.index('by_status', ['statusId'])
.index('by_user', ['userId'])
.index('by_user_and_category', ['userId', 'categoryId'])
```

### Consistency

Stay consistent within each table:

- `userId` + `by_user` OR `authorId` + `by_author`
- Don't mix naming styles

## Function Organization

### Group by Domain

One file per domain/entity:

```ts
// convex/items.ts
export const create = mutation(...)
export const get = query(...)
export const list = query(...)
export const remove = mutation(...)
export const update = mutation(...)

// convex/topics.ts
export const get = query(...)
export const getBySlug = query(...)
export const list = query(...)
```

### Shared Helpers in lib/

```ts
// convex/lib/permissions.ts
export async function getCurrentUser(ctx: QueryCtx | MutationCtx) {
  const identity = await ctx.auth.getUserIdentity();
 
 if (!identity) {
    return null
  };

  const user = await ctx.db
    .query('user')
    .withIndex('by_email', (q) => q.eq('email', identity.email!))
    .first();

  return user;
}
```

## Authorization Pattern

Always check auth in mutations:

```ts
// ✅ Always verify user and ownership
export const update = mutation({
  handler: async (ctx, args) => {
    const user = await getCurrentUser(ctx);
    if (!user) {
      throw new Error('Unauthorized')
    };

    const resource = await ctx.db.get(args.id);
    if (resource.userId !== user._id) {
      throw new Error('Not authorized');
    }

    // Now safe to update
  },
});
```

## Data Enrichment Pattern

Enrich data with relationships in queries:

```ts
export const list = query({
  handler: async (ctx) => {
    const items = await ctx.db.query('items').collect();

    return Promise.all(
      items.map(async (item) => {
        const category = await ctx.db.get(item.categoryId);
        const owner = await ctx.db.get(item.userId);

        return {
          ...item,
          category,
          owner: { name: owner?.name, image: owner?.image },
        };
      }),
    );
  },
});
```

## Best Practices

### Avoid Redundant Indexes

```ts
// ❌ Redundant - only need the second one
.index('by_user', ['userId'])
.index('by_user_and_category', ['userId', 'categoryId'])

// ✅ Only define what you need
.index('by_user_and_category', ['userId', 'categoryId'])
.index('by_category', ['categoryId'])
```

Use the more specific index for all queries, even when you don't need all fields.
